%I A397207 #41 Jul 22 2026 22:26:43
%S A397207 91,148,175,259,325,370,481,496,592,925,1480,2275,2368,2752,2821,3367,
%T A397207 3700,4375,5461,5920,6364,6475,6541,6700,7471,7936,8125,9250,9472,
%U A397207 12025,14701,14800,14911,17200,19201,19900,21931,23125,23680,29341,37000,37888,39700
%N A397207 Composite numbers d such that the period k of the decimal expansion of 1/d is divisible by 3 and divides d-1, and the three blocks of length k/3 of the repetend of 1/d sum to a multiple of 10^(k/3) - 1.
%C A397207 The 3-block analog of A394717: split the repetend into 3 blocks instead of 2. Every prime p (other than 2 and 5) with 3 | k passes (Gupta and Sury, 2005); optional for composites.
%C A397207 Equivalently: d is a term iff d is in A351396, d' divides 10^(2k/3) + 10^(k/3) + 1, and 3 | k; d' is d with factors of 2 and 5 removed.
%C A397207 For a term, the three blocks sum to 10^(k/3) - 1, never a higher multiple (Lewittes 2006, Theorem 7).
%C A397207 In contrast to the 2-block/halves case, even terms do appear (148 is the first). Every term is == 1 (mod 3).
%C A397207 If p^2 divides a term for a prime p other than 2 and 5, then p is a base-10 Wieferich prime (A045616). The first nonsquarefree term is 237169 = 487^2. The next, 56598313^2, is also a term.
%C A397207 259 is a term but it fails the halves test; 1729 passes halves but is not a term — the two block counts are independent.
%H A397207 Barry Smyth, <a href="/A397207/b397207.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1266</a>
%H A397207 A. Gupta and B. Sury, <a href="https://math.colgate.edu/~integers/f19/f19.pdf">Decimal expansion of 1/p and subgroup sums</a>, Integers 5 (2005), #A19.
%H A397207 J. Lewittes, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0605182">Midy's Theorem for Periodic Decimals</a>, arXiv:math/0605182 [math.NT], 2006.
%H A397207 Étienne Midy, <a href="https://archive.org/details/1014596483">De quelques propriétés des nombres et des fractions décimales périodiques</a>, 1836.
%e A397207 259 = 7*37 is a term: 1/259 = 0.003861003861..., the period 6 is divisible by 3 and divides 258, and 00 + 38 + 61 = 99 = 10^2 - 1.
%e A397207 148 = 2^2*37 is a term: the period of 1/148 is 3 (that of 1/37, whose repetend is 027), 3 divides 147, and 0 + 2 + 7 = 9.
%e A397207 1729 = 7*13*19 is not a term: its period 18 is divisible by 3 and divides 1728, but the three 6-digit blocks of 1/1729 sum to 000578 + 368999 + 421631 = 791208, not a multiple of 999999.
%o A397207 (Python)
%o A397207 from sympy import isprime, n_order
%o A397207 def ok(d):
%o A397207     if d < 4 or isprime(d):
%o A397207         return False
%o A397207     dr = d
%o A397207     while dr % 2 == 0: dr //= 2
%o A397207     while dr % 5 == 0: dr //= 5
%o A397207     if dr == 1:
%o A397207         return False
%o A397207     k = n_order(10, dr)
%o A397207     if k % 3 or (d-1) % k:
%o A397207         return False
%o A397207     t = k // 3
%o A397207     return (1 + pow(10, t, dr) + pow(10, 2*t, dr)) % dr == 0
%o A397207 print([d for d in range(40000) if ok(d)])
%Y A397207 Subsequence of A351396. Cf. A394717 (halves analog), A045616 (the only primes whose squares can divide terms).
